Filter Response Interactivity
Visualize the frequency response of an RC filter. Adjust \(R\) and \(C\) to move the cutoff.

viewof r_filt = Inputs.range([100, 10000], {value: 1000, step: 100, label: "Resistance (Ω)"});
viewof c_filt = Inputs.range([0.01, 10], {value: 1, step: 0.1, label: "Capacitance (μF)"});






















The plot shows a Log-Log scale. Notice that at low frequencies, the gain is 1. As we pass the critical frequency (fc), the gain drops off at 20dB per decade. If we need a sharper drop, we would cascade multiple filters.

Interactive: First-Order Step Response
Explore how the time constant \(\tau\) affects the sensor’s speed.

viewof tau = Inputs.range([0.1, 5.0], {value: 1.0, step: 0.1, label: "Time Constant (τ)"});
viewof final_val = Inputs.range([1, 10], {value: 5, step: 1, label: "Final Value (bf)"});






















Use the slider to increase the time constant. Notice how a larger tau results in a “sluggish” sensor. In ECE, we often aim for sensors with the smallest possible tau to ensure real-time tracking of process variables.

Interactive: Second-Order Damped Oscillation
Adjust damping and frequency to see the transient error.

viewof damping = Inputs.range([0.1, 2.0], {value: 0.5, step: 0.1, label: "Damping (a)"});
viewof freq = Inputs.range([0.5, 5.0], {value: 2.0, step: 0.1, label: "Frequency (fn)"});






















This visualization shows a typical underdamped second-order response. In engineering design, we often aim for “critical damping” to reach the final value as quickly as possible without excessive oscillation.

Example 15: Step‑by‑Step Solution

Compute initial and final outputs from static transfer function:

\[
\begin{aligned}
b_i &= (33 \text{ mV}/{}^\circ\text{C})(20^\circ\text{C}) = 660 \text{ mV} \\
b_f &= (33 \text{ mV}/{}^\circ\text{C})(41^\circ\text{C}) = 1353 \text{ mV}
\end{aligned}
\]

Apply first‑order time response at \(t = 0.75\) s:

\[
\begin{aligned}
b(t) &= b_i + (b_f - b_i)\left[1 - e^{-t/\tau}\right] \\
b(0.75)
&= 660 + (1353 - 660)\left[1 - e^{-0.75/1.5}\right] \\
&= 660 + 693\left[1 - e^{-0.5}\right] \\
&\approx 660 + 693\cdot(1 - 0.6065) \\
&\approx 932.7 \text{ mV}
\end{aligned}
\]

Convert output back to indicated temperature:

\[
T_\text{indicated}
= \frac{b(t)}{33\text{ mV}/{}^\circ\text{C}}
= \frac{932.7}{33}
\approx 28.3^\circ\text{C}
\]

Error relative to actual:

\[
\Delta T = T_\text{indicated} - T_\text{actual}
= 28.3^\circ\text{C} - 41^\circ\text{C}
= -12.7^\circ\text{C}
\]
So, at 0.75 s, the sensor under‑reports by about 12.7 °C.






Warning


Time response analysis applies to the sensor output (voltage here), not to the actual process temperature.




Discuss “design implications”:

If you used this sensor to control a heater with fast dynamics, the controller might continue to heat because it “thinks” the temperature is still low.
Slow sensors can cause overshoot in control loops even if the plant is not inherently oscillatory.

Interactive: Tuning Response Types
Adjust the parameters below to see the difference between Damped and Cyclic (Underdamped) responses to a setpoint change.

viewof damping = Inputs.range([0.1, 1.5], {value: 0.7, step: 0.1, label: "Damping Ratio"});
viewof frequency = Inputs.range([0.5, 5.0], {value: 2.0, step: 0.1, label: "Natural Frequency"});






















Slide the damping ratio. Below 1.0, you see ‘Cyclic’ response (oscillations). Above 1.0, you see ‘Damped’ response (no overshoot). As engineers, we choose the tuning based on the process needs.

Interactive Solution 4: Error Accumulator
Adjust the uncertainties to see the impact on total system error.

viewof u1 = Inputs.range([0, 5], {value: 2.0, step: 0.1, label: "Block 1 Accuracy (%)"});
viewof u2 = Inputs.range([0, 5], {value: 0.8, step: 0.1, label: "Block 2 Accuracy (%)"});






















Notice how the RMS value is always lower than the Worst-Case. In industrial design, we often use RMS because it is statistically rare for every single component to be at its maximum error limit simultaneously in the same direction.

